Turns out the JavaScript spread syntax (...three dots) is a lot simpler to understand than the MDN docs make it out to be: https://t.co/ejBTIu0St0

Here‚Äôs how I understand it anyway:

..."string" becomes s,t,r,i,n,g

...[1,2,3] becomes 1,2,3

...{one: 1, two: 2} becomes one: 1, two: 2

So it just gives you each element comma separated. Pretty much. Right?

(also can be used in destructuring but that‚Äôs another story)
